The paper deals with the problem of storing a set of strings in a compact form, which is a fundamental data structure problem in computer science. The paper also mentions various applications such as Natural Language Processing, indexing text collections, Web engines, Web mining, RDF graphs, Internet routing, and Bioinformatics, which are covered by several sub-categories of arXiv CS. Based on this, the most likely sub-category is cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms), which deals with fundamental data structure problems. The next likely sub-category is cs.IR (Information Retrieval), which deals with indexing and searching large collections of text data. The paper also mentions databases, which falls under cs.DB (Databases). The paper proposes new compression techniques, which can be considered as a machine learning problem, and hence cs.LG (Machine Learning) can also be a likely sub-category. Finally, the paper mentions the need for efficient algorithms, which can be covered by cs.CC (Computational Complexity).
